        {
            ["Institution"] = "University of North Florida",
            ["Faculty advisor"] = "J. Scott Kelly",
            ["Project type"] = "Directed independent study",
            ["Duration"] = "Fall 2025 semester",
            ["Focus"] = "Cyber team process analysis, gap planning, and training recommendations",
            ["Status"] = "Deliverables 1-2 complete; Deliverable 3 in progress"
        }
    };
}

@await Html.PartialAsync("_ResumeDetailHeader", header)

<p>
    During my last semester, I shifted from competition participation to a directed independent study under
    Professor <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/jscottkelly/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">J. Scott Kelly</a>.
    The project focused on why our team underperformed, why peer schools performed better, and what process changes were needed to improve outcomes.
</p>

<h2 class="h5 mt-4">Deliverables</h2>
<ol>
    <li>
        <strong>As-Is analysis:</strong> documented current team preparation and competition execution processes,
        including first-impression process and training gaps.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>To-Be model + gap analysis:</strong> defined improved process procedures, mapped weaknesses to
        targeted strengths, and produced a detailed gap analysis between current and desired state.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Penetration testing course outline:</strong> proposed course structure updates, including what to
        add, change, or remove relative to current coursework and syllabus structure.
    </li>
</ol>

<h2 class="h5 mt-4">Findings and Recommendations (Deliverables 1-2)</h2>
<p>
    The first two deliverables focused on documenting the team's current-state process and defining a realistic student-run future-state model.
    This section summarizes the core findings and recommendations without publishing full artifacts yet.
</p>

<h3 class="h6 mt-3">As-Is Findings</h3>
<ul>
    <li>Preparation was typically limited to short weekly practices, with little full competition simulation.</li>
    <li>Mock competition frequency was low, which reduced role execution and reporting practice under pressure.</li>
    <li>Readiness entering competition season was inconsistent, with gaps in team-wide depth and coordination.</li>
    <li>Common undertrained areas included Windows/Active Directory defense, triage workflow, and recovery execution.</li>
    <li>Operational issues during competition often included communication breakdowns, role ambiguity, and weak change tracking.</li>
</ul>

<h3 class="h6 mt-3">To-Be Recommendations</h3>
<ul>
    <li>Shift to continuous year-round preparation instead of a mostly seasonal training rhythm.</li>
    <li>Increase competition-like simulations, including inject handling, communication, and executive-style reporting.</li>
    <li>Prioritize team-level resilience over isolated individual performance metrics.</li>
    <li>Improve leadership accountability and implementation consistency against existing team governance expectations.</li>
    <li>Build a larger readiness pipeline so performance is not dependent on only one or two high-skill members.</li>
</ul>

<p class="text-muted mb-0">
    Deliverables 1 and 2 are complete; Deliverable 3 is in progress and all artifacts will be published together after study completion.
</p>

<h2 class="h5 mt-4">Related Experience</h2>
<p class="mb-0">
    <a asp-controller="Resume" asp-action="ExperienceCyberSecurityTeam">View UNF Cyber Security Team experience</a>
</p>

<ul>
    <li>Focused process analysis and improvement planning for team outcomes</li>
    <li>Produced formal documentation and recommendations for execution changes</li>
    <li>Connected research findings to practical training and curriculum decisions</li>
</ul>
